# Implement k-means ## Overview ## Setup ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(workflows) library(parsnip) library(tidyclust) library(tidyverse) library(tidymodels) d <- read_csv("./data/mu_weighted_soil_props.csv") %>% select(-contains("comp_pct")) old_names <- colnames(d) new_names <- str_replace_all(old_names, "_r_value", "") colnames(d) <- new_names ``` ::: Reminder of what the data look like: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} head(d) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: Reminder of the transformations I chose to improve variable distributions and make them normal-ish. - Clay: square root - Organic matter: log10 or ln - CEC: log10 or ln - Bulk density: cubed (dB \^ 3) - EC: None - pH: None - Carbonates: square root - LEP: 1+ ln OR 1 + log10 - Ksat: log10 or ln - AWC: log10 or ln ## Pre-process data This is something specific to the `tidymodels` modeling workflow, and I like it because it's very explicit about how variables are transformed (pre-processed) prior to initializing the model. Here I apply some transformations to achieve more normal distributions, and then standardize (`step_normalize`) by subtracting the mean and divide by 1 sd. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} rec_spec <- recipe(~., data = d) %>% update_role(mukey, new_role = "ID") %>% step_log(om, cec7, ksat, awc) %>% step_log(lep, offset = 1) %>% step_poly(dbthirdbar, degree = 3) %>% step_sqrt(claytotal, caco3) %>% step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) rec_spec ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Recipe Inputs: role #variables ID 1 predictor 10 Operations: Log transformation on om, cec7, ksat, awc Log transformation on lep Orthogonal polynomials on dbthirdbar Square root transformation on claytotal, caco3 Centering and scaling for all_numeric_predictors() ``` ::: ::: ## Specify model and define workflow For now, set this up to run with just one value of k, then scale up to multiple values so we can compare performance. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # uses default k.means algorithm from stats pkg kmeans_spec <- k_means(num_clusters = 5) nclust <- c(2:10) kmeans_nclust <- map(nclust, ~k_means(num_clusters = .x)) km_df <- data.frame(n_clust = nclust) km_df %>% mutate(kmeans_spec = map(nclust, ~k_means(num_clusters = .x))) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} # define workflow using our model and prep info defined above kmeans_wf <- workflow(rec_spec, kmeans_spec) ``` ::: ## Fit the model All the steps above were related to specifying different aspects of this model. Now we can actually "run" the k-means. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} kmeans_fit <- fit(kmeans_wf, data = d) extract_cluster_assignment(kmeans_fit) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} extract_centroids(kmeans_fit) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: ## Later: Define main data structure Because one of our objectives is to determine a reasonable number of clusters, we will be running the k-means algorithm multiple times with different values of `k`. Here, I set up a dataframe that will serve as the landing spot for our model objects and the associated model performance metrics. See "Exploratory Clustering" section of [this tidymodels article](https://www.tidymodels.org/learn/statistics/k-means/). ::: {.cell} ::: ##
